metadata.help: The thickness of the thin film layer on a surface. Use for materials such as multitone car paint or soap bubbles.
metadata.label: Thin Film Thickness

metadata.help: If true the surface is double-sided and represents an infinitely thin shell. Suitable for thin objects such as tree leaves or paper.
metadata.label: Thin Walled

metadata.help: Transmission of light through the surface for materials such as glass or water. The greater the value the more transparent the material.
metadata.label: Transmission

metadata.help: Color tint on the transmitted light.
metadata.label: Transmission Color

metadata.help: Specifies the distance light travels inside the material before its becomes exactly the transmission color according to Beer's law.
metadata.label: Transmission Depth

metadata.help: Dispersion amount, describing how much the index of refraction varies across wavelengths.
metadata.label: Transmission Dispersion

metadata.help: Additional roughness on top of specular roughness. Positive values blur refractions more than reflections, and negative values blur refractions less.
metadata.label: Transmission Roughness

metadata.help: Scattering coefficient of the interior medium. Suitable for a large body of liquid or one that is fairly thick, such as an ocean, honey, ice, or frosted glass.
metadata.label: Transmission Scatter

metadata.help: The amount of directional bias, or anisotropy, of the scattering.
metadata.label: Transmission Anisotropy
